nes were manufactured between 1956 and 1975 and distributed nationwide. The majority of the owners appear to be institutions such as schools and \"Little League\" teams, but some machines are privately-owned. The machines were sold under various brand names including: \"Olympia, \" \"Olympic,\" \"Champ,\" \"Blazer,\" \"Super Blazer,\" \"Pro-Blazer,\" \"Range Blazer, \" \"Range, \" \"Master,\" \"Mentor,\" \"Pro-Trainer,\" and \"Professional.\" The pitching machines are operated by electricity or gasoline engine. Even when the machine is turned off or unplugged, however, if the pitching arm is cocked in approximately the \"10 o\'clock position,\" the machine can fire if jarred or subjected to vibration. Consequently, the Commission warns that the machines should be locked up to prevent accidents and should never be left in areas where children can reach them. Before locking up the machine, CPSC advises that the pitching arm cable be disconnected carefully from the coil spring. The Commission has filed a lawsuit in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia seeking to compel the manufacturer and distributors of the machines to provide a guard for the pitching arm at no cost to the purchaser. Without such a guard, the Commission warns, the machines are dangerous and may cause severe injury. The Commission urges people not to use these machines.', 'Baseball Pitching Machines Warning', '2014-12-17', 'Master automatic baseball pitching machines', 'https:--www.cpsc.gov-Recalls-1978-CPSC-Warns-On-Hazardous-Baseball-Pitching-Machines'),
